<!-- ═══ Context ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="context" style="margin-top: 64px;">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Context</h2>
        <p class="body-text">ICS had a sprawling product portfolio including a B2C gaming portal, a B2B agent dashboard, and a sports event back-office — all requiring support across PC, Mobile Web (H5), and Native App. Without systematic standards, the team faced severe Operational Debt:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Fragmented Development</h4>
        <p class="body-text">Every time a new product line launched, the team redefined typography (H1-H6), spacing, and color palettes from scratch, burning significant time on repetitive foundational work.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Cross-Platform Inconsistency</h4>
        <p class="body-text">The same brand had mismatched border radii and gray scales between App and Web, undermining product professionalism.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">High Communication Overhead</h4>
        <p class="body-text">Front-end engineers eyeballed spacing (producing arbitrary values like 9px, 13px), leading to excessive pixel-pushing during QA.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">My Role</h4>
        <p class="body-text">As the senior designer on the team, I proactively identified these structural problems and proposed building the company's first Design System. I led the entire effort end-to-end — from defining standards, designing the architecture, and building the Token Pipeline to driving cross-departmental adoption.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Twin-Layer Architecture ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="twin-layer">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>The "Twin-Layer" Architecture</h2>
        <p class="body-text">The core tension was: a Design System demands consistency, but a B2C gaming portal (high-saturation, playful) and a B2B agent dashboard (dark, premium) are worlds apart visually. A rigid one-size-fits-all system would make every product look the same; no system at all would leave the wheel-reinventing problem unsolved.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Foundation Layer — Write Once, Use Everywhere</h4>
        <p class="body-text">This layer served as the "laws of physics" shared by all products, ensuring cross-platform consistency:</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Foundation Cards Grid -->
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="foundation-cards-grid">
            <!-- Row 1: Base-4 Scale, Typography, Grayscale -->
            <div class="foundation-cards-row">
                <div class="foundation-card-wrapper">
                    <img src="/images/ics/foundation_layer_base.png" alt="Base-4 Size Scale" class="foundation-card-img">
                    <p class="foundation-card-info">Defined a set of primitive size tokens built on a base-4 progression, serving as the single source of sizing truth for typography, spacing, and component dimensions.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="foundation-card-wrapper">
                    <img src="/images/ics/foundation_layer_typography.png" alt="Typography" class="foundation-card-img">
                    <p class="foundation-card-info">Unified H1-H6 hierarchy, providing a universal structural skeleton regardless of product line.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="foundation-card-wrapper">
                    <img src="/images/ics/foundation_layer_grayscale.png" alt="Grayscale" class="foundation-card-img">
                    <p class="foundation-card-info">Gray tones appear frequently across all UI text, borders, and backgrounds with consistent steps, so I defined a standardized grayscale as a shared foundational palette.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Row 2: Spacing, Branding Color -->
            <div class="foundation-cards-row">
                <div class="foundation-card-wrapper">
                    <img src="/images/ics/foundation_layer_spacing.png" alt="Spacing" class="foundation-card-img">
                    <p class="foundation-card-info">Strictly enforced 8px grid (with 4px fine-tuning allowed), eliminating arbitrary values like 13px or 7px so engineers could calculate layouts through math.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="foundation-card-wrapper">
                    <img src="/images/ics/foundation_layer_branding_color.png" alt="Branding Color" class="foundation-card-img">
                    <p class="foundation-card-info">To ensure brand identity permeated every product line, we kept the core Branding Color series in the Foundation Layer — guaranteeing primary brand colors remained consistent regardless of which Theme was applied on top.</p>
                </div>
                <!-- Empty cell keeps 3-column alignment -->
                <div class="foundation-card-wrapper"></div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Creative Layer — Theming Strategy</h4>
        <p class="body-text">On top of the shared foundation, I customized themes for different target audiences. This layering meant that when launching a new product, the team only needed to decide "which Theme to apply" — not redefine every foundational style from scratch.</p>
    </div>

