<!-- ═══ Core Design Challenges ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="core-challenges">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Core Design Challenges</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Bridging Design and Code — The Token Pipeline</h4>
        <p class="body-text">The twin-layer architecture solved the design-side standards problem, but if the handoff method remained "screenshots + annotations," the execution gap on the engineering side would persist. My most critical contribution in this project was building an automated pipeline from design to code:</p>
    </div>
    <div class="image-block">
        <div class="token-pipeline">
            <img src="/images/ics/design_token.png" alt="Design token pipeline" style="width:100%;height:100%;object-fit:cover;top:0;left:0;border-radius:0;">
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Design Tokens Pipeline</h4>
        <p class="body-text">I established a variable system within Figma and used plugins to directly export JSON-formatted Style Dictionary files to the front-end team. Every token had a clear naming hierarchy (e.g., color.primary.500, spacing.lg), ensuring design intent could be directly consumed by code.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h4 class="phase-label">Single Source of Truth</h4>
        <p class="body-text">When a color value was adjusted on the design side, front-end only needed to update the JSON file for site-wide synchronization — no manual CSS edits required. This eliminated the classic pain point of "design changed but engineering didn't follow," achieving truly engineered collaboration.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Impact & Learnings ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="impact">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Impact &amp; Learnings</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h3>Zero-Setup for New Projects</h3>
        <p class="body-text">When launching new projects, front-end and designers directly adopted the Foundation Library, skipping 1-2 weeks of baseline styling setup and jumping straight into business logic design.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h3>Focus on Creativity</h3>
        <p class="body-text">Designers were freed from the tedium of repeatedly defining button styles, redirecting their energy to differentiated visual expression and user experience across B2B/B2C.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="text-block">
        <h3>Design-to-Code Accuracy</h3>
        <p class="body-text">Through the Token Pipeline and 8pt Grid constraints, the accuracy between development output and design specs improved dramatically, significantly reducing pixel-correction issues during QA.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ Reflection ═══ -->
<div class="section" id="reflection">
    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Reflection: What I'd Do Differently</h2>
        <p class="body-text">Involve engineers earlier. This Design System was primarily built by me on the design side in the early stages — I defined the complete standards first, then handed them off to the front-end team. While the Token Pipeline ultimately achieved smooth integration, if I could do it over, I would bring front-end engineers into the architecture design phase to co-define token naming conventions and data structures. The benefit: engineers could surface technical constraints and implementation insights early, preventing the design side from defining standards that are "theoretically perfect but awkward to implement" — while also building engineering ownership of the system to accelerate adoption and maintenance.</p>
    </div>
</div>
